Carnitine palmitoyltransferase is a mitochondrial enzyme responsible for the transfer of acti-
vated FAs inside the mitochondria for
β
-oxidation. Literature data regarding the dietary effects
on carnitine palmitoyltransferase activity are ambiguous. Smink et al. (2010) [
] reported that
the hepatic activities of carnitine palmitoyltransferase were similar in chickens fed diets supple-
mented with sunflower oil or palmoil. Sanz et al. (2000) [
], however, found that the activity
of carnitine palmitoyltransferase was higher in heart extracts of chickens fed a diet enriched
with sunflower oil than in chickens fed a diet containing tallow. Preferential oxidation of
PUFAs over SFAs in chickens was reported by Newman et al. (2002) [
]. In our study, the
mRNA expression of this enzyme was low in the livers of chickens fed a diet supplemented with
lard and high in the livers of chickens fed diets supplemented with rapeseed oil or palmoil.
